        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>There are no other kinds. Every piece of state is either stored or computed. Understanding this reduces the entire domain to a single question: <strong>how are the dependencies between computed and stored nodes managed?</strong></p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Manual vs Automatic Capture</h2>

  <p>The traditional approach — RxSwift's <code>combineLatest</code>, Kotlin's <code>combine</code>, Zustand's selectors — requires the developer to <strong>manually wire</strong> each dependency:</p>

  <Code code={captureNaiveCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>The breakthrough of graph-based systems is <strong>automatic capture</strong>: you write the computation, and the system discovers the dependencies for you:</p>

  <Code code={captureAutoCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>But how does this actually work? The closure <code>{`{ a.value + b.value }`}</code> is just code — the system can't statically analyze it to know which nodes are accessed. The answer lies in the <strong>ambient pattern</strong>.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>The Ambient Pattern (How Capture Actually Works)</h2>

  <p>The key insight: the closure is an <strong>escaping closure</strong>. It is not executed when it's defined — it's executed later, when someone accesses the computed node's value. At execution time, the system can track which nodes are read.</p>

  <p>The mechanism uses a thread-local (or context-local) variable — often called <code>currentNode</code> — to track who is currently being evaluated:</p>

  <Code code={captureStackCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>This is the technique that makes Jotai's <code>get()</code>, Atoms' <code>context.watch()</code>, Riverpod's <code>ref.watch()</code>, and swift-state-graph's property access all work. The specific API differs, but the underlying mechanism is the same: <strong>set a context before executing the closure, observe accesses during execution, build edges from those accesses</strong>.</p>

  <h3>Nested Computed Values (Stack Behavior)</h3>

  <p>When a computed node depends on another computed node, the system uses a <strong>stack</strong> to track the nesting:</p>

  <Code code={captureNestedCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>The stack ensures that each node's dependencies are attributed to the correct node, even when computations are deeply nested.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Conditional / Dynamic Dependencies</h2>

  <p>Because dependencies are discovered at <strong>runtime</strong> (not statically), they can change based on conditions:</p>

  <Code code={conditionalCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>This is a capability that manual wiring systems (RxSwift, Combine, StateFlow) struggle with. With <code>combineLatest(a, b, d)</code>, you'd subscribe to all three regardless of which branch executes. With automatic capture, you only depend on what you actually read.</p>

  <p>Each time the computed node is re-evaluated, <strong>all previous dependencies are cleared and rebuilt from scratch</strong>. This ensures the dependency graph always reflects the current reality.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>SwiftUI's body Is a Computed Node</h2>

  <p>SwiftUI's view <code>body</code> is, at its core, exactly the same as a computed node in a dependency graph:</p>

  <Code code={swiftuiBodyCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>This is why SwiftUI can achieve fine-grained updates without the developer explicitly subscribing to anything. The <code>body</code> closure is an escaping closure — it's only executed when the view needs to render. During execution, the system (AttributedGraph) tracks which <code>@State</code> / <code>@Observable</code> properties are accessed, building the dependency edges automatically.</p>

  <p>If a property is never accessed in the current execution path, the view has no dependency on it, and changes to that property will <strong>not</strong> trigger a re-evaluation of <code>body</code>.</p>

  <p>This is not SwiftUI-specific magic. It's the same ambient capture pattern used by Jotai, swift-state-graph, and every other graph-based system. SwiftUI just happens to be the most widely-used implementation of it.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Lazy Invalidation (Dirty Flags, Not Eager Recomputation)</h2>

  <p>When a stored value changes, what happens to its dependents? This is where push and pull diverge most clearly:</p>

  <Code code={dirtyFlagCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>The pull/lazy approach has a critical advantage: <strong>multiple source changes are naturally batched</strong>. If <code>a</code>, <code>b</code>, and <code>d</code> all change before anyone reads a computed value, only one recomputation happens — with all three new values already in place. No intermediate states. No glitching.</p>

  <h3>The setNeedsLayout Analogy</h3>

  <p>UIKit developers already know this pattern intimately:</p>

  <Code code={setNeedsLayoutCode} lang="swift" />

  <p>The two-method pattern (<code>setNeedsLayout</code> + <code>layoutIfNeeded</code>) exists precisely to separate <strong>invalidation</strong> from <strong>recomputation</strong>. Graph-based state management does the same thing: mark dirty, then recompute on access.</p>

  <p>This is also why SwiftUI doesn't immediately re-render a view when <code>@State</code> changes. It marks the view's body as "potentially dirty" and batches the re-evaluation into the next render pass — exactly like <code>setNeedsLayout</code>.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Mental Models: Waterfall vs Bird's-Eye View</h2>

  <p>A useful way to visualize the difference between push and pull:</p>

  <p><strong>Push (RxSwift / Combine / StateFlow)</strong> is like a <strong>waterfall</strong>. Values flow downward from upstream to downstream. When the source emits, the value cascades through the stream. You stand at the bottom and receive whatever falls. If the waterfall is too fast, you get overwhelmed (backpressure).</p>

  <p><strong>Pull (AttributedGraph / Jotai / swift-state-graph)</strong> is like a <strong>bird's-eye view</strong>. You look down at the graph from above. You can see that something changed — a node is marked dirty — but you don't know the new value yet. You only compute it when you need it. Multiple changes can accumulate, and when you finally look, you see the latest state of everything at once.</p>

  <p>Both can express the same data flow patterns (A + B = C). The difference is <strong>who drives the computation</strong>: the producer (push) or the consumer (pull).</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Why This Matters</h2>

  <p>Understanding the internals — the ambient pattern, stack-based capture, lazy invalidation — reveals that graph-based state management is not a new invention. It's the application of well-established computer science (DAGs, topological sorting, lazy evaluation) to the problem of UI state management.</p>

  <p>The same fundamental algorithms appear in:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spreadsheets</strong> (Excel, Google Sheets) — the original reactive cell engine</li>
    <li><strong>Build systems</strong> (Make, Bazel) — dependency-driven recomputation</li>
    <li><strong>Package managers</strong> (SPM, npm) — dependency resolution as a DAG</li>
    <li><strong>Garbage collectors</strong> — reference graph traversal</li>
    <li><strong>UI layout engines</strong> (Auto Layout, UIKit's layout system) — constraint-based dependency solving</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Once you see the pattern, you see it everywhere. The question for any state management library is simply: <strong>does it make the developer manage the graph manually, or does the runtime handle it?</strong></p>
</DocsLayout>
